name: Mr. Alpenfuchs
tweet: #bitcoin’s arrival heralds a new dawn of property ownership. Now anyone can own digital property which is superior in many ways to real estate and physical property  “But you can’t live in #bitcoin”,  So what…   Neither can squatters.

name: Mr. Alpenfuchs
tweet: A #bitcoin node in the network will not even pass on a invalid claim on your property should it hear one. So a fraudster can’t propagate his fraudulent message. But with real estate they can bribe a registrar to amend their  registry and assume ownership of your property.

name: Mr. Alpenfuchs
tweet: #bitcoin’s property registry - it’s ledger - is unassailable, incorruptible, immutable, equitable, permission-less, and enduring. The consensus protocol adjudicates and enforces your property rights. An army of miners expend energy defending your property.

name: Mr. Alpenfuchs
tweet: #bitcoin is fungible and can be sold to anyone in the world. Real Estate is not fungible, and often restricts who can own it.   The market of buyers for #bitcoin is 8 billion people.

name: Mr. Alpenfuchs
tweet: 3) #bitcoin is portable, you can take the monetary equivalent of a whole city block with you in your pocket or transfer it to anyone/anywhere in the world in minutes, or even to the space station. Land and buildings are immovable.

name: Mr. Alpenfuchs
tweet: 2) Land, even if in a desirable location, can become impaired by bad local governments, rising crime, etc., just like San Francisco these days.   #bitcoin doesn’t have this problem.

name: Mr. Alpenfuchs
tweet: #Bitcoin is a superior store of value compared to real estate, here’s why:   1) Buildings age, need to be maintained (ongoing cost) or become condemned and then incur  a cost to demolish.   Not #Bitcoin
